\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of THPNE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's start with a couple of definitions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\shape italic
completely mixed strategy
\shape default
 if it puts positive probability on all of player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's pure strategies.
 A strategy profile 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is completely mixed if all players are playing a completely mixed strategy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prevent confusion, let's assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ 1,...,I\right\} $
\end_inset

, then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A NE strategy profile 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is trembling hand perfect 
\shape italic
if there exists
\shape default
 a sequence of completely mixed strategy profiles 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\sigma_{n}\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\sigma_{n}=\sigma$
\end_inset

 and such that for all players 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a best response to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{-in}$
\end_inset

 for a large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of THPNE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's look at a few examples to clarify the definition above:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For Example 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exa:THPNE"

\end_inset

 above, consider the NE where player 1 plays 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

U
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and player 2 plays 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

M
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 From the definition of THP, we need to consider completely mixed strategy
 
\shape italic
profiles
\shape default
, so let's assume that player 1 is playing a completely mixed strategy,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

, where he places 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\epsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

 probability on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

U
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

 probability on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

D
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Also let's assume that player 2 is playing a completely mixed strategy,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

, where she places 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\epsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

 probability on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

M
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 probability on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

L
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{n}=\frac{1}{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{n}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 So we do have a sequence of strategy profiles of the form in the definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Note that as 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{n}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, the strategy profiles converge to the NE under consideration, [U,M].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's look at the expected utilities of player 1 given the completely
 mixed strategy of player 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
U_{1}(Up;\sigma_{2}^{*}) & = & 4\epsilon_{n}+2(1-\epsilon_{n})=2+2\epsilon_{n}\\
U_{1}(Down;\sigma_{2}^{*}) & = & 5\epsilon_{n}+2(1-\epsilon_{n})=2+3\epsilon_{n}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because we're looking at values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

 arbitrarily close to zero (but not equal to zero, because we're considering
 completely mixed strategy profiles), 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}(Down;\sigma_{2}^{*})>U_{1}(Up;\sigma_{2}^{*})$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $3\epsilon>2\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we conclude that the candidate [U,M] is 
\shape italic
not
\shape default
 trembling hand perfect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the definition of THPNE states that there is 
\shape italic
no
\shape default
 sequence of completely mixed strategies 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\sigma_{n}\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\sigma_{n}=\sigma$
\end_inset

 and such that for all players 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a best response to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{-in}$
\end_inset

 for a large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 We didn't do that above, but for purposes of this class it is sufficient.
 
\end_layout

