\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Instead of checking to see whether we have convergence to the candidate
 strategy as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, I use 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and drop the subscripts.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We need to come up with a completely mixed strategy for each player that
 at its limit is equal to the strategy being played in our equilibrium of
 interest.
 Consider the following:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{1\epsilon}=\left[\frac{1}{2}-\epsilon,\,\frac{1}{2}-\epsilon,\,2\epsilon\right];\,\sigma_{2\epsilon}=\left[\frac{1}{3}-\epsilon,\,\frac{2}{3}+\frac{\epsilon}{4},\,\frac{3}{4}\epsilon\right]\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now we calculated the expected utilities for each of the players.
 Let's start with player 1:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
U_{1}(U) & = & 3\left(\frac{1}{3}-\epsilon\right)+1\left(\frac{2}{3}+\frac{\epsilon}{4}\right)+4\left(\frac{3}{4}\epsilon\right)=\frac{5}{3}+\frac{\epsilon}{4}\\
U_{1}(M) & = & 1\left(\frac{1}{3}-\epsilon\right)+2\left(\frac{2}{3}+\frac{\epsilon}{4}\right)+1\left(\frac{3}{4}\cdot\epsilon\right)=\frac{5}{3}+\frac{\epsilon}{4}.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}(M)=U_{1}(U)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, we've found a sequence of completely mixed strategies which converge to
 the NE and for which the mixed strategy is a best response (because the
 payoffs are the same given player 2's mixed strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{2\epsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Try this for player 2 and you should see that the same holds.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
U_{2}(L) & = & 1\left(\frac{1}{2}-\epsilon\right)+3\left(\frac{1}{2}-\epsilon\right)+1\left(2\epsilon\right)=2-2\epsilon\\
U_{2}(C) & = & 0\left(\frac{1}{2}-\epsilon\right)+4\left(\frac{1}{2}-\epsilon\right)+1\left(2\epsilon\right)=2-2\epsilon.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

